,Recommended,245430,18083106,"Posted: 18 September, 2015",all,Snow Crash,"Make no mistake, this game is a masterpiece.  It's also incredibly difficult.  Use a walkthrough if you ever get stuck (I recommendtk421.net/wizardry/wiz7walk.shtml).Very very basic tips:1) Initial party composition should have:a) 2-3 melee fighter types (Fighter, Valkyrie, Lord, Samurai, Monk, Ninja).  I always recommend Valkyries over Lords as they are functionally the same class, but Valkyries gain levels faster.b) a defensive caster/healer (Priest or Alchemist)c) a thief-type (Thief, Bard, or Ranger).  I highly recommend a Bard.d) an offensive caster (Mage, Psionic, or Alchemist)2) Save often, and make backups of your saves.  It's easy to irreparably ♥♥♥♥ something up in a wway that will make you glad you had a save from 45 minutes prior.  Also, QUIT-NOSAVE if your friend.3) Many skills gain points on successful use.  Important ones include Skullduggery (gain a point when you successfully pick a lock or disarm a trap) and Ninjitsu (gain a point with every X number of succesful Hide attempts).  Ninjitsu affects your Monk/Ninja's intrinsic defensive ability.4) Crucial spells to gain access to: Heal Wounds, Cure Lesser Condition, Cure Poison, Identify.  Identify items before equipping/using them whenever possible.5) Quest items cannot be sold, but they can be dropped.  Do not drop anything unless you're pretty sure you don't need it anymore, and drop used quest items in a safe and easy-to-remember location in case you're wrong.6) There's a Journey Map Kit in the forest behind your initial spawn location.7) Explore and enjoy!  The game world is huge and immersive, and the humor is perfectly tongue-in-cheek."
